'''Nikolas Tomas "Nik" Stauskas''' (born October 7, 1993) is a  [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[college basketball]] player.  A [[Canada|Canadian]] native, Stauskas plays for the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines]] and is playing his freshman season for the [[2012<U+2013>13 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2012<U+2013>13 team]]. Stauskas is of Lithuanian heritage, but has represented the [[Canada men's national basketball team|Canadian men's national basketball team]].

After spending two of his secondary school years in Ontario at [[Loyola Catholic Secondary School]] and representing the Canadian National Team at the 2009 [[FIBA Americas Under-16 Championship]], Stauskas moved to [[South Kent, Connecticut]] to attend [[South Kent School]] for a year, but did not play basketball there due to a hip injury. He then transferred to [[St. Mark's School (Massachusetts)|St. Mark's School]] in [[Southborough, Massachusetts]] where he excelled at [[high school basketball]] for two years, leading the school to back-to-back [[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]] (NEPSAC) Class AA Championship Games. The team won the NEPSAC championship in Stauskas' 2012 senior season, and he was the championship game MVP.  He was also selected to the NEPSAC All-Class AA team.

As a freshman at Michigan, he moved into the starting lineup in the team's seventh game, based on his excellent shooting. By the end of December of that year he had been named Big Ten Conference Freshman of the Week three times. At the end of January, he was named to the [[Wayman Tisdale Award]] <U+22C5>(USBWA National Freshman of the Year) top 12 midseason list.

==Background==
Until 2009, Stauskas played for [[Loyola Catholic Secondary School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball.on.ca/site/content/April20091.pdf|title=Time Out|accessdate=2012-12-03|publisher=Ontario Basketball}}</ref> He averaged 32.0 [[Point (basketball)|points]], 14.0 [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] and 7.5 [[assist (basketball)|assists]] in 2009&ndash;10 and 15.0 points, 5.0 rebounds and 5.0 assists in 2008&ndash;09.<ref name=NS11/> Stauskas spent the 2009&ndash;10 academic year at [[South Kent School]], but the forested rural campus made him homesick and he transferred to [[St. Mark's School (Massachusetts)|St. Mark's School]] the following year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/high-school/post/_/id/3713/canadian-raising-at-st-marks|title=Canadian Raising at St. Mark's|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2010-12-11|author=Hall, Brendan|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He missed the 2009&ndash;10 basketball season as a result of a hip injury.<ref name=NS11>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/stauskas_nik00.html|title=Nik Stauskas 11|accessdate=2012-12-02|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball]] [[head coach]] [[John Beilein]] became familiar with Stauskas during the Summer 2010 NBA camp prior to Stauskas' junior year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/111611aaa.html|title=Michigan Roundtable Wrap-Up #4|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2011-11-16|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> Stauskas visited Michigan that summer and was also being recruited by [[Villanova Wildcats men's basketball|Villanova]], [[Iowa State Cyclones men's basketball|Iowa State]], [[Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball|Georgetown]], [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish men's basketball|Notre Dame]], [[Florida Gators men's basketball|Florida]] and [[Providence Friars men's basketball|Providence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jet7basket.com/Canadian-Basketball-High-Scool/catching-up-with-nik-stauskas.html|title=Catching Up With Nik Stauskas|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2010-08-04|work=[[Crown Magazine]]|author=Loung, Steven}}</ref> By the time he arrived at St. Mark's, he was expected to be an All-State performer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/high-school/post/_/id/3676/preseason-all-state-hoops-squads|title=Preseason All-State Hoops squads|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2010-12-08|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> In the 2011 [[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]] (NEPSAC) Class AA Championship game, Stauskas led St. Mark's in scoring with 17 points against the [[Nerlens Noel]]'s [[Tilton School]], but St. Marks lost 72&ndash;56.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/high-school/post/_/id/5542/tilton-four-peats-with-class-aa-title|title=Tilton four-peats with Class AA title|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2011-03-07|author=Hall, Brendan|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On March 26, 2011, Stauskas made a verbal commitment to Michigan, making him the second member of the school's recruiting class of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umhoops.com/2011/03/26/nik-stauskas-commits-to-michigan/|title=Nik Stauskas Commits to Michigan|accessdate=2011-03-27|date=2011-03-26|author=Burkhardt, Dylan|work=UMHoops.com| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110501054518/http://www.umhoops.com/2011/03/26/nik-stauskas-commits-to-michigan/| archivedate= 1 May 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/high-school/post/_/id/6656/st-marks-stauskas-commits-to-michigan|title=St. Mark's Stauskas commits to Michigan|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2011-03-28|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> 

Prior to his senior year, ESPN named him as one of the top 25 [[Three-point field goal|three point shooters]] in the national class of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/high-school/post/_/id/11050/stauskas-papale-named-top-3-pt-shooters|title=Stauskas, Papale named top 3-pt. shooters|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2011-11-03|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> At the time of their November 2011 [[National Letter of Intent]] signings, Stauskas, [[Glenn Robinson III]] and [[Mitch McGary]] gave Michigan a consensus top 10 entering class for its 2012 class.<ref name=>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/persistence-pays-off-john-beilein-offers-first-comments-on-mitch-mcgary-glenn-robinson-iii/|title=Persistence pays off: John Beilein offers first comments on Mitch McGary, Glenn Robinson III|accessdate=2012-11-14|date=2011-11-10|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> Stauskas visited Michigan along with future teammate Robinson to see the 61&ndash;56 [[New Year's Day]] 2012 victory by the [[2011<U+2013>12 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2011<U+2013>12 Wolverines team]] over [[2011<U+2013>12 Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball team|Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/john-beilein-laughs-off-analysts-prediction-of-michigan-in-the-2013-final-four/|title=John Beilein laughs off analyst's prediction of Michigan in the 2013 Final Four|accessdate=2012-11-30|date=2012-01-09|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=320010130|title=Freshman Trey Burke lifts Michigan to close win over Minnesota|accessdate=2012-11-30|date=2012-01-01|publishr=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Then Stauskas led St. Mark's to 67&ndash;57 victory in a 2012 Hoophall Classic contest with 16 points against [[Friends' Central School|Friends Central]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/michigan-basketball-recruits-mitch-mcgary-and-nik-stauskas-earn-wins-on-national-stage/|title=With video: Michigan basketball recruits Mitch McGary and Nik Stauskas earn wins on national stage|accessdate=2012-11-30|date=2012-01-16|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> As the season progressed, Stauskas (and Robinson) improved in the national player ratings to offset McGary's slide and maintain a top-rated class.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/michigan-basketball-recruit-mitch-mcgary-falls-in-espncom-rankings/|title=ESPN.com: Michigan basketball recruit Mitch McGary falls in ESPN.com rankings|accessdate=2012-12-01|date=2012-01-24|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/recruiting-analyst-explains-mitch-mcgarys-ranking-slide-says-michigan-basketball-still-has-terrific/|title=Recruiting analyst explains Mitch McGary's ranking slide, says Michigan basketball still has 'terrific' '12 class|accessdate=2012-12-01|date=2012-01-31|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/despite-mitch-mcgarys-slide-2012-michigan-basketball-class-rated-higher-than-michigan-state/|title=Despite Mitch McGary's slide, Michigan basketball's 2012 class rated higher than Michigan State's|accessdate=2012-12-01|date=2012-02-07|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> He scored 19 to lead his school to a 59&ndash;53 2012 NEPSAC Class AA Championship game victory over Noel's Tilton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/high-school/post/_/id/14655/nepsac-st-marks-59-tilton-n-h-53|title=NEPSAC: St. Mark's 59, Tilton (N.H.) 53|accessdate=2012-11-30|date=2012-03-04|author=Smith, Andy|publishr=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Stauskas earned the NEPSAC championship game MVP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newenglandrecruitingreport.com/news/article/2418/NEPSAC-Finals-Sunday-Recap.php|title=NEPSAC Finals: Sunday Recap|accessdate=2012-03-08|date=2012-03-05|work=New England Recruiting Report|author=Bradley, Christian}}</ref><ref name=VNSrtdaboeftMbt/> He was selected to the 2012 All-NEPSAC Class AA team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/michigan-basketball-signees-nik-stauskas-mitch-mcgary-receive-honors/|title=Michigan basketball signees Nik Stauskas, Mitch McGary receive honors|accessdate=2012-11-30|date=2012-03-27|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> Following these honors, Stauskas' stock and rankings continued to rise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/michigan-basketball-signee-glenn-robinson-iii-now-no-11-prospect-nationally-per-rivalscom/|title=Michigan basketball recruit Glenn Robinson III ranked No. 11 in nation by Rivals.com|accessdate=2012-12-01|date=2012-04-11|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref>
