Stauskas began his college career with the expectation that he would be a sharpshooter based on his performance in [[three-point field goal]] drills in which he has raised the bar for the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2012/10/michigans_nik_stauskas_and_mat.html|title=Michigan's Nik Stauskas and Matt Vogrich could finally give John Beilein a consistent deep threat in Ann Arbor|accessdate=2012-11-30|date=2012-10-31|publisher=Michigan Live LLC.|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> In the championship rounds of the 2012 [[NIT Season Tip-Off]] tournament at [[Madison Square Garden]] on November 21 and November 23, Michigan defeated [[2012<U+2013>13 Pittsburgh Panthers men's basketball team|Pittsburgh]] and [[2012<U+2013>13 Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball team|Kansas State]], respectively, to win the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/112312aaa.html|title=Hardaway's MVP Effort Leads U-M to First NIT Season Tip-Off Title|accessdate=2012-11-24|date=2012-11-23|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=323280130|title=Michigan shrugs off Kansas State to win NIT Season Tip-off|accessdate=2012-11-24|date=2012-11-23|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=323260221|title=No. 4 Michigan stifles Pittsburgh to reach NIT Season Tipoff final|accessdate=2012-11-24|date=2012-11-21|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On November 26, Stauskas earned Big Ten Freshman of the Week honors for his NIT tournament performance in which he averaged 12.5 points and 4.5 [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=323280130|title=Kansas St 57 (5-1, 0-0 away); (4) Michigan 71 (5-0, 3-0 home)|accessdate=2012-11-26|date=2012-11-23|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=323260221|title=Pittsburgh 62 (4-1, 0-0 away); (4) Michigan 67 (4-0, 3-0 home)|accessdate=2012-11-24|date=2012-11-21|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref name="bigten2">{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/112612aaa.html|title=Michigan and Minnesota Earn Big Ten Weekly Awards|accessdate=2012-11-26|date=2012-11-26|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=BigTen.org}}</ref> On November 27, Michigan defeated its first ranked opponent of the season, [[2012<U+2013>13 NC State Wolfpack men's basketball team|NC State]] (#18/18), in the [[ACC<U+2013>Big Ten Challenge]] behind [[Trey Burke]]'s first career [[double-double]] which included a career-high 11 assists, no [[Turnover (basketball)|turnover]]s and 18 points, and a then-career-high 20 points from Stauskas in a 79&ndash;72 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=323320130|title=Trey Burke, Michigan able to stave off NC State|accessdate=2012-11-28|date=2012-11-27|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  After that game, [[ESPN]] analyst [[Dan Dakich]] described Stauskas as the most underrated freshman in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/mi/wolverines/2012/11/espns_dan_dakich_nik_stauskas/|title=ESPN's Dan Dakich: Nik Stauskas 'may be the best freshman in the country' that no one is talking about|accessdate=2012-11-30|date=2012-11-28|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> That week, Burke called Stauskas the best shooter he has ever played with.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2012/11/michigan_freshman_nik_stauskas_2.html|title=Michigan freshman Nik Stauskas turning Crisler Center into his own Canadian backyard|accessdate=2012-12-01|date=2012-11-27|publisher=Michigan Live LLC.|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> On December 1 against [[2012<U+2013>13 Bradley Braves men's basketball team|Bradley]], Stauskas made his first career regular season start and posted a new career-high 22 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=323360071|title=(3) Michigan 74 (7-0, 1-0 away); Bradley 66 (5-2, 3-1 home)|accessdate=2012-12-01|date=2012-12-01|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/120112aac.html|title=Postgame Notes: #3 Michigan 74, Bradley 66|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2012-12-01|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> For his first two 20 point performances, he repeated as Big Ten Freshman of the Week on December 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/120312aaa.html|title=Nebraska and Michigan Earn Big Ten Weekly Awards: Huskers' Almeida records 20 points, 10 rebounds, shoots 90 percent from the field in Challenge win |accessdate=2012-12-03|date=2012-12-03|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=BigTen.org}}</ref> On December 29, against the [[2012<U+2013>13 Central Michigan Chippewas men's basketball team|Central Michigan]], Stauskas posted 19 points on 5-for-8 three point shooting. His 5 three pointers and 7 rebounds were career-highs, earning him his third Big Ten Freshman of the Week on December 31.<ref name=CM7M8>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=323640130|title=Cent Michigan 73 (7-6, 1-3 away); (2) Michigan 88 (13-0, 9-0 home)|accessdate=2012-12-30|date=2012-12-29|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref name="bigten6">{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/123112aaa.html|title=Illinois and Michigan Earn Weekly Conference Honors|accessdate=2012-12-31|date=2012-12-31|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=BigTen.org}}</ref> 

Entering the day of December 31, Stauskas led the nation in three point [[field goal percentage]].<ref name="bigten6"/> This is somewhat confusing because various sources have various eligibility thresholds. ESPN reports leaders based on a 2 three point attempts per game minimum,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/statistics/player/_/stat/3-points|title=NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Player 3-Point Shooting Statistics - 2012-13|accessdate=2013-01-01|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> while BigTen.org only requires a minimum of 1.5 attempts per game for eligibility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/stats/2012-2013/confldrs.html#conf.wki|title=The Automated ScoreBook: Overall Statistics|accessdate=2013-01-01|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=BigTen.org}}</ref>  [[NCAA.org]] requires a minimum of 2.5 made per game, and Stauskas had been the leader since the December 9 weekly report.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/stats/StatsSrv/rankings?sportCode=MBB|title=2012-13 Men's Basketball Statistics|accessdate=2013-01-01|date=2012-12-30|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]}}</ref>  On January 31, Stuaskas and Robinson were named to the [[Wayman Tisdale Award]] (USBWA National Freshman of the Year) top 12 midseason list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/013113aad.html|title=Trio of Wolverines Named to Midseason List of National Awards|accessdate=2013-02-04|date=2013-01-31|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref>

==International play==
Stauskas played for the 2009 [[FIBA Americas Under-16 Championship]] held in [[Argentina]]. He helped the [[Canada men's national basketball team]] to a Bronze medal which qualified them for the [[2010 FIBA Under-17 World Championship]]. Stauskas averaged 9.4 points per game in the tournament,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://turkey2010.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/player/p/pid/75914/sid/4054/tid/257/_/2009_FIBA_Americas_U16_Championship_for_Men/index.html|title=2009 FIBA Americas U16 Championship for Men: Canada: 5 - Nikolas Stauskas|accessdate=2012-12-02|publisher=[[FIBA]]}}</ref> including a game-high 21 points in a 126&ndash;78 loss against the United States team led by [[Bradley Beal]] and [[James Michael McAdoo]] on June 20, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://turkey2010.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/game/p/gid/A/grid/15/rid/7041/sid/4054/tid/257/_/2009_FIBA_Americas_U16_Championship_for_Men/statistic.html|title=2009 FIBA Americas U16 Championship for Men: Box Score: Game: USA vs CANADA (Group 15)|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2009-06-20|publisher=[[FIBA]]}}</ref> Stauskas was invited to train with the Senior Men<U+2019>s National Team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketball.ca/canada-basketball-announces-senior-men-s-national-team-camp-and-invited-athletes--p151673|title=Senior Men's National Team - Training Camp Roster|accessdate=2012-12-02|publisher=Basketball.ca}}</ref>

==Personal==
His father is Paul Stauskas, and his mother is Ruta.<ref name=NS11/><ref name=VNSrtdaboeftMbt>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/versatile-nik-stauskas-at-ease-with-his-role-ready-to-make-a-splash-for-the-michigan-basketball-team/|title=Versatile Nik Stauskas ready to do a bit of everything for the Michigan basketball team|accessdate=2012-11-30|date=2012-05-15|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref>  He has dual Canadian and Lithuanian citizenship, but is only eligible to play for Canada in international play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurobasket.com/Lithuania/basketball.asp?NewsID=295621&showcomments=1&Women=1&Women=0#c|title=Martynas Pocius selected the top Lithuanian playing abroad in last week's games|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2012-11-16|publisher=[[Eurobasket]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurobasket.com/Lithuania/basketball.asp?NewsID=297625&showcomments=1&Women=1&Women=0#c|title=Jonas Valanciunas selected the top Lithuanian playing abroad in last week's games|accessdate=2012-12-02|date=2012-11-30|publisher=[[Eurobasket]]}}</ref> Geographically, Michigan is closer to Stauskas' parents home in Ontario than any other major Division I school, according to Stauskas<!--Syracuse?-->.<ref name=VNSrtdaboeftMbt/> When he tweeted a [[Christmas Eve]] 2012 video of himself making 45 of 50 three point shots,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NStauskas11/status/283291575004565504|title=@NStauskas11 status|accessdate=2013-01-03|date=2012-12-24|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Stauskas, Nik}}</ref> [[Dick Vitale]] replied 14 minutes later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DickieV/status/283295163760128000|title=@DickieV status|accessdate=2013-01-03|date=2012-12-24|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Vitale, Dick}}</ref>

